{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621235"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16680"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16680"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70535"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9371"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5393"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23677"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70535"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA public health researcher is studying the occurrence of type 2 diabetes in a community of 10,000 adults. During one year of observation, 50 new cases of type 2 diabetes are diagnosed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the incidence rate of type 2 diabetes in this population?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["5 cases per 1,000 person-years","0.005 cases per person-year","50 cases per 10,000 person-years","500 cases per 100,000 person-years","5,000 cases per million person-years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003E5 cases per 1,000 person-years\u003C/strong\u003E is calculated by dividing the number of new cases (50) by the population at risk (10,000) over one year, then multiplying by 1,000 to express it as a rate per 1,000 person-years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other expressions are mathematically equivalent but less conventional:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.005 cases per person-year\u003C/strong\u003E represents the raw rate without scaling, which is less commonly used in epidemiological reporting.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50 cases per 10,000 person-years\u003C/strong\u003E uses a larger population denominator that makes the rate more difficult to interpret quickly.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500 cases per 100,000 person-years\u003C/strong\u003E scales the rate to a much larger population size than necessary for this frequency of disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5,000 cases per million person-years\u003C/strong\u003E expresses the rate using an unnecessarily large population denominator that does not aid interpretation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncidence rate is a fundamental measure in epidemiology that quantifies the occurrence of new cases of disease in a population over time. For conditions like type 2 diabetes, rates are typically expressed per 1,000 person-years for clarity and ease of interpretation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incidence measures the number of new cases of a condition in a population over a specific time period.","Incidence rate is calculated by dividing new cases by the population at risk during the time period.","Incidence differs from prevalence, which measures existing cases at a single point in time.","Incidence rates are typically expressed per 1,000 person-years for common conditions."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001, accessed 12 Dec. 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16680"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T19:07:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T19:08:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9371"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}